1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. d5 {This has never been the really
main continuation here, but the move is quite principled and should be
regarded as one of the cornerstones of the whole Zaitsev system. The ensuing
structure is highly assymetrical and, although abstractly speaking the mutual
weaknesses should compensate for each other, over the board it is not always
easy to have the right orientation, especially when confronted with a new idea.
} Nb8 13. Nf1 Nbd7 14. N3h2 Nc5 ({In some earlier comments, I considered the
prophylactic} 14... h6 {to be necessary, before breaking White's centre, but
the fashion does not seem to agree with me...} 15. Ng4 {Naiditsch,A (2664)
-Svidler,P (2742)/Dortmund 2006/CBM 114/[Marin,M] (1/2-1/2, 59)} (15. Qf3 {
Bruzon Bautista,L (2667)-Morozevich,A (2731)/Biel 2006/CBM 114/[Marin,M] (0-1,
53)})) 15. Bc2 c6 16. b4 Ncd7 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. Bg5 h6 {An interesting moment.
This move might look like a loss of time.} ({Why not develop the queen with} 
18... Qc7 {instead? The answer is given by practical games and has an abstract
explanation as well. Let's see.} 19. Bxf6 {(Anyway; for the moment, it might
seem that ...h6 is a loss of time, indeed!)} Nxf6 20. Ng4 Be7 {This is the
almost unanimous answer here.} ({In the event of} 20... Nxg4 {White can play}
21. hxg4 $1 {increasing his control on the light squares and obtaining some
chances for a kingside attack along the h-file. With his queen on d8 still,
Black could have played ...d5 here, but now this is impossible. The following
game was played between two veterans and I believe we should trust White's
play, because he had his best times in a period when many basic principles of
the Ruy Lopez were established.} Rac8 22. Bb3 Bd7 23. Rc1 Be7 24. Ne3 Bg5 25.
Nd5 Qb8 26. Rc2 Rc6 27. g3 Qc8 28. f3 Be6 29. Qd3 Bd8 30. Kg2 $16 {Jansa,V 
(2482)-Klovans,J (2433)/Arvier 2006/CBM 114 ext (1-0, 41)[%cal Ge1h1]}) 21.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Navara had had this position with White and failed to obtain
anything tangible. However, when he chose the whole setup with Black, an
unpleasant surprise awaited him.} 22. Bb3 $1 $146 (22. Ne3 Bg5 23. Nf5 g6 24.
Ne3 Rad8 25. Qd3 Bxe3 26. Qxe3 d5 $11 {Navara,D (2656)-Ivanov,A (2565)/
Khanty-Mansiysk 2007 (1-0, 45)}) 22... a5 ({The drawbacks of the early queen
move can be seen after} 22... Bd7 23. Ne3 $1 {when Her majesty remains exposed
to the knight move to d5. Winning the pawn with} Qxc3 {does not absolve Black
from problems after} 24. Nd5 Qd4 25. Qf3 $36) 23. bxa5 $1 {White spoils his
queenside structure in order to maintain a firm grip on the light squares and
the initiative.} Rxa5 24. Qf3 Bd7 25. Ne3 Be6 (25... Qxc3 $6 26. Qh5 $16 {
[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge3d5]} g6 $2 27. Qf3 $1 $18 {In the event of the "obvious"}
Kg7 {White has a choice between} 28. Nf5+ {and 28.Qxf6!+}) 26. Nd5 {Once again,
the queen's exposure is obvious.} Bxd5 ({Black's position after} 26... Qd8 $5 {
is far from appealing (especially that now the queen maneouvre can be
considered a loss of time with respect to ...h6), but this might have been his
last chance to get a survivable position.}) 27. Bxd5 $16 {The presence of
opposite coloured bishops makes White's attack hard to resist.} Rc8 28. Re3 Qd7
29. Rd1 Bd8 30. Qh5 Bb6 31. Rf3 Rf8 32. Bxf7+ $1 Rxf7 33. Rxd6 Qa7 34. Qxf7+
Qxf7 35. Rxf7 Kxf7 36. Rxb6 $18 {Almasi,Z (2691)-Navara,D (2656)/Reggio Emilia
2008/ (1-0, 58). The conclusion is that in certain cases the best square for
the queen is... d8! The explanation is that from the initial square the
balance between control on the oposite wings and the centre is relatively good.
This only applies if the rooks do not need communication, as in the cases when
the position is open and play has a dynamic character.}) 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Ng4
Nxg4 21. Qxg4 ({As mentioned above,} 21. hxg4 $6 {can be met by} d5 $1 $36)
21... Rc8 {[%csl Gc3]} (21... d5 $6 {allows White activate his play with} 22.
exd5 Qxd5 23. Bb3 {1-0 Adams,M (2742)-Ponomariov,R (2727)/Linares 2002/CBM 088/
[Wedberg] (76)[%cal Yf1e3,Ya1d1,Ye3f5,Yb3f7,Yd1d7]}) (21... Bd7 {is likely to
transpose to the game continuation.}) 22. Bb3 Bd7 23. Qf3 Be6 {Both sides have
more or less completed their regroupings. Black has managed to neutralise the
enemy bishop's pressure and exerts some pressure against the c3-pawn and the
c4-square himself. However, his other bishop remains passive for the time
being. The position has a static character, but both sides can consider
abruptly changing the situation.} 24. Red1 $5 $146 {Why this rook? Leko
obviously intends to play a4 at some moment, considering that he does not need
a rook on the e-file.} ({The exchange} 24. Bxe6 fxe6 {only strengthens Black's
centre. Bacrot proved the position to be entirely playable for Black.} 25. a4
Qd7 (25... Qc7 26. axb5 axb5 27. Ra3 Ra8 28. Rea1 Rxa3 29. Rxa3 Be7 30. Qd3 Qc6
31. Ne3 Rc8 32. g3 Bg5 33. h4 Bxe3 34. Qxe3 Kh7 $11 35. Ra5 Qxc3 36. Qxc3 Rxc3
37. Rxb5 Rc4 38. Rb6 Rxe4 39. Rxd6 Rxb4 40. Rxe6 Rb5 41. Kg2 {1/2-1/2 Leko,P 
(2763)-Bacrot,E (2729)/Dortmund 2005/CBM 108}) 26. axb5 axb5 27. Qd3 Qc6 28.
Ra3 d5 29. exd5 exd5 30. Ne3 d4 31. cxd4 exd4 32. Qxd4 Re4 33. Qa1 Bxb4 $132 {
