Rc2 a5 26. Qd3 Bxb3 27. axb3 axb4 28. Ne3 bxc3 29. Rxc3 Rxc3 30. Qxc3 Bg5 31.
Nd5 $44 {Anand,V (2792)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2683)/Mainz 2007/CBM 120 (1-0, 45)}) (
24. Rad1 Re7 (24... a5 $5 {looks more ambitious.}) 25. Rd3 Rec7 26. Ng3 Qg5
$132 {1/2-1/2 Vouldis,A-Cela,A/Athens 1997/EXT 2004 (44)}) 24... Qg5 {Adams
spotted the abstract drawback of Leko's novelty: the e4-pawn is insufficiently
defended! Well, this was obvious in fact, but the manner he chose to take
advantage of it is rather original.} ({In the event of} 24... a5 {White could
have played} 25. Bxe6 fxe6 26. a4 $5 {, when the rook placement chosen by Leko
would have been entirely justified.}) (24... Re7 $5 {[%cal Ge7c7]}) 25. Rd3 Qf4
26. Qe2 {It might seem that Black just lost time. Soon he will be pushed back
with the daring queen...} (26. Qxf4 exf4 {[%cal Ge8e4]} 27. Nd2 Be7 $132 {
[%cal Ge7f6]}) 26... Bxb3 $5 27. axb3 d5 {The only logical continuation.
Otherwise, Black would be just worse, with his queen rather misplaced on f4.
However, after opening the a-file, Leko's strategy looks justified anyway.} 28.
Rxd5 {After this overcautious move, White's advantage will be microscopic.} ({
The critical continuation is} 28. exd5 e4 29. Re3 Qe5 (29... Qd6 30. Ng3 {
could more or less transpose.}) 30. Rxa6 f5 {Apparently, White is under some
pressure, but he can strive for counterplay with} 31. Ng3 Qxd5 32. Qh5 {Here,
we can see a drawback of the move ...h6: with the pawn on h7, Black would
simply play ...g6. Well, there is no such thing as the perfect move,
especially when you play with Black. Anyway, only further practical testing
will reveal the objective merits of Adams' plan.}) 28... Rxc3 29. Rxa6 Rxb3 30.
Nd2 Rxb4 31. g3 Qg5 32. Rb6 Rd8 33. Rbxb5 Rxd5 34. Rxd5 {The position has
become almost symmetrical and the number of pawns has been reduced drastically.
However, White's knight is stronger than the bishop in such positions with
pawns on just one wing.} Rb2 35. h4 Qf6 36. Qe3 Rc2 37. Nf3 Bc5 $5 {Adams opts
for a practical decision. The queen ending is a theoretical draw and he will
prove that he knows how to defend it!} ({Playing on with all the pieces is
slightly dangerous, for instance} 37... Bd6 38. Kg2 Bc7 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc7b6]
} 39. Qd3 Ra2 40. Qb3 Ra8 (40... Re2 $2 41. Qc4 $18 {[%csl Gc7,Ge2]}) 41. h5
$14 {with domination on light squares for White and... long suffering ahead
for Black.}) 38. Rxc5 Rxc5 39. Qxc5 Qxf3 40. Qxe5 $14 h5 41. Qb8+ Kh7 42. Qf4
